  "summary": "Salivary gland cancer is a rare type of head and neck cancer that forms in the tissues of the salivary glands. These glands produce saliva, which aids in chewing, swallowing, digestion, and oral hygiene. The cancer may not cause symptoms initially, but can manifest as a lump or swelling in the ear, cheek, jaw, lip, or inside the mouth, along with potential fluid drainage from the ear, difficulty swallowing or opening the mouth, and facial numbness, weakness, or pain. Malignant growths can involve nerves, leading to facial nerve paralysis, pain, and paresthesias. Fixation of a lump, ulceration, and induration of the mucosa are also indicators of malignancy.",
